pageContext.claim: “I did something for a man named Scooter Libby, who was not treated fairly in the eyes of many. I've heard this for many years, was not treated fairly. And Liz [Cheney] and her father -- and they came out early for me. Actually, her father came out like almost immediately for me, and it was interesting because I didn't know him. I liked him, I respected him, but I didn't know him really. But he came out very early. It was a very important moment, actually, for me because who the hell was supporting me? Everyone thought I was just playing games, right? They said, 'He doesn't really mean this. He's just having fun.' You call this fun?”
pageContext.analysis: Former vice president Richard B. Cheney endorsed Trump around the time he clinched the GOP nomination in May, 2016, after months of distancing himself. Cheney was especially upset at Trump's criticism of the invasion of Iraq, saying Trump sounded like a "liberal Democrat."
